articles.headline: TARP Bailout to Cost Less Than Once Anticipated
articles.snippet: The reviled mother of all bailouts — $700 billion to banks, insurance and auto companies — will expire at a fraction of that cost and may even turn a profit.
articles.abstract: The reviled mother of all bailouts — $700 billion to banks, insurance and auto companies — will expire at a fraction of that cost and may even turn a profit.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON  Even as voters rage and candidates put up ads against government bailouts, the reviled mother of them all  the $700 billion lifeline to banks, insurance and auto companies  will expire after Sunday at a fraction of that cost, and could conceivably earn taxpayers a profit.

articles.headline: Foreclosures Slow as Document Flaws Emerge
articles.snippet: Evictions are expected to slow as officials look into questionable foreclosure methods revealed by two big home lenders.
articles.abstract: Evictions are expected to slow as officials look into questionable foreclosure methods revealed by two big home lenders.
articles.lead_paragraph: The foreclosure machinery that has forced millions of Americans out of their homes is beginning to seize up as some lenders and their lawyers are accused of cutting corners in their pursuit of rapid home repossessions.

articles.headline: Patents Ending, Eli Lilly Chases New Drugs
articles.snippet: The company is facing losing patent protection on drugs that accounted for 74 percent of its sales in 2009.
articles.abstract: The company is facing losing patent protection on drugs that accounted for 74 percent of its sales in 2009.
articles.lead_paragraph: INDIANAPOLIS  John C. Lechleiter walks a mile to work every morning to think about the day ahead. He walks home in the evening, he says, “to try to forget about it.”

articles.headline: Insurer Cuts Health Plans as New Law Takes Hold
articles.snippet: Principal Financial said that it planned to stop selling health insurance, another sign of upheaval emerging among insurers as the health law starts to take effect.
articles.abstract: Principal Financial said that it planned to stop selling health insurance, another sign of upheaval emerging among insurers as the health law starts to take effect.
articles.lead_paragraph: The Principal Financial Group announced on Thursday that it planned to stop selling health insurance, another sign of upheaval emerging among insurers as the new federal health law starts to take effect.

articles.headline: Accord Paves Way for Re-election of Iraq Premier
articles.snippet: The deal allows for the return of an anti-American Shiite Islamic movement that could reshape U.S. relations.
articles.abstract: The deal allows for the return of an anti-American Shiite Islamic movement that could reshape U.S. relations.
articles.lead_paragraph: BAGHDAD  Prime Minister Nuri Kamal al-Maliki of Iraq appeared almost assured of a second term in office on Friday after securing the support of an anti-American Shiite Islamic movement whose return to political power could profoundly complicate relations with the United States.
